<subSubSection id="C30EB4BB837E7E01A3C0FD31B5636E08" pageId="8" pageNumber="219" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BABE730837E7E01A3C0FD31B5636E08" blockId="8.[151,1437,680,1103]" pageId="8" pageNumber="219">
<emphasis id="B9603B22837E7E01A3C0FD31B72F6FBC" bold="true" box="[151,274,680,706]" pageId="8" pageNumber="219">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species is recognized within the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C149CB3837E7E01A056FD31B5A46FBC" authorityName="Fieber" authorityYear="1860" baseAuthorityName="Fieber" baseAuthorityYear="1860" box="[769,921,680,706]" class="Insecta" family="Alydidae" genus="Megalotomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="219" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9603B22837E7E01A056FD31B5A46FBC" box="[769,921,680,706]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="219">Megalotomus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by a combination of the following characters: body size relatively moderate, 12.0–14.0 mm in length, reddish brown or yellowish brown, with small and red spots on legs and corium of forewing; posterior region of ocellus with black spot; posterior angle of pronotum acute, but not ending in sharp spine; surcapsular spines of male genital capsule curved, tapering to a point, with the apices close to each other; parameres elongate, broadly extended and strongly curving in middle, with a large and a small spine midway, terminating with 3–5 small spines on both sides.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
